In many scenarios, utilizing a Set is commonly considered when aiming to hold a collection of unique objects. However, the options available vary based on your specific objectives. From my perspective, these two approaches are among the most straightforward.

#### 1. Use HashSet and override the hashCode() and equals().


```Java
public class Student {
    private long id;
    private String name;

    public Student(long id, String name) {
        this.id = id;
        this.name = name;
    }

    @Override
    public boolean equals(Object o) {
        if (this == o) return true;
        if (o == null || getClass() != o.getClass()) return false;

        Student student = (Student) o;

        if (id != student.id) return false;
        return Objects.equals(name, student.name);
    }

    @Override
    public int hashCode() {
        int result = (int) (id ^ (id &gt;&gt;&gt; 32));
        result = 31 * result + (name != null ? name.hashCode() : 0);
        return result;
    }
}
```

```Java
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Student student1 = new Student(1, &quot;Elon&quot;);
        Student student2 = new Student(1, &quot;Elon&quot;);
        Student student3 = new Student(2, &quot;Elon&quot;);

        Set&lt;Student&gt; students = new HashSet&lt;&gt;();
        students.add(student1);
        students.add(student2);
        students.add(student3);

        System.out.println(students.size()); // 2
        System.out.println(students); // This will print student1 and student3 (because student2 is a duplicate)
    }
}
```

